## What authentication methods does gh support?

GitHub CLI supports:

### 1. Browser Authentication (Recommended)

```bash
gh auth login
```

Opens a browser and completes authentication using a device code.

---

### 2. Personal Access Token (PAT)

```bash
gh auth login --with-token
```

Then provide a GitHub Personal Access Token.

Useful for:

- Servers
- Automation
- CI/CD pipelines

---

### 3. SSH Authentication

Configure Git operations to use SSH keys.

Example:

```bash
ssh-keygen -t ed25519
```

Add the public key to GitHub and authenticate using SSH.

---

### 4. GitHub Actions Authentication

Uses:

```text
GITHUB_TOKEN
```

Automatically provided inside GitHub Actions workflows.

Used for:

- CI/CD
- Automated repository operations

---

## Summary

| Method | Use Case |
|----------|----------|
| Browser Login | Daily development |
| Personal Access Token | Automation & servers |
| SSH Keys | Secure Git operations |
| GITHUB_TOKEN | GitHub Actions workflows |


# Task 2: Working with Repositories Using GitHub CLI (gh)

### 1. Create a New GitHub Repository from the Terminal

Create a public repository with a README:
```bash 
gh repo create gh-cli-test \
  --public \
  --add-readme \
  --clone
```

What happens?
- Creates repository `gh-cli-test`
- Make it public
- Adds a README.md
- Clones it locally automatically

Expected output:
```
✓ Created repository Anuj2402/gh-cli-test on github.com
  https://github.com/Anuj2402/gh-cli-test
Cloning into 'gh-cli-test'...

```
OUTPUT From github: 
![alt text](image.png)

### 2. Clone a Repository Using `gh`

Instead of:
```bash 
git clone https://github.com/user/repo.git
```
Use:
```bash 
gh repo clone cli/cli
```
Example with my own repo:
```bash 
gh repo clone Anuj2402/devops-git-practice
```
- This clones the repository locally.

### 3. View Details of One of Your Repositories

Run:
```bash 
gh repo view devops-git-practice
```

or
```bash 
gh repo view Anuj2402/devops-git-practice
```

Example output:
```bash 
name:    devops-git-practice
owner:   Anuj2402
visibility: Public
description:
```
### 4. List All Your Repositories

Run:
```bash 
gh repo list
```

Example:
```bash 
Anuj2402/devops-git-practice
Anuj2402/90DaysOfDevOps
Anuj2402/gh-cli-test
```
Limit results:
```bash 
gh repo list --limit 20
```

### 5. Open a Repository in Your Browser

Open current repository:
```bash 
gh repo view --web
```
Open a specific repository:
```bash 
gh repo view Anuj2402/devops-git-practice --web
```
- default browser opens automatically.

### 6. Delete the Test Repository
- Be careful. This permanently deletes the repository.

Delete:
```bash 
gh repo delete Anuj2402/gh-cli-test
```
GitHub CLI will ask:
```
Are you sure you want to delete this repository?
```
Type:
```
y
```
- You may also be asked to enter the repository name for confirmation.

Force delete (not recommended):
```bash 
gh repo delete Anuj2402/gh-cli-test --yes
```
ERROR WE can encounter 
```bash 
anujrai@anujrai-mn4561 90DaysOfDevOps % gh repo delete Anuj2402/gh-cli-test --yes
HTTP 403: Must have admin rights to Repository. (https://api.github.com/repos/Anuj2402/gh-cli-test)
This API operation needs the "delete_repo" scope. To request it, run:  gh auth refresh -h github.com -s delete_repo
```
Run This command to solve this : 
```bash 
gh auth refresh -h github.com -s delete_repo
```



Output:
```
anujrai@anujrai-mn4561 90DaysOfDevOps % gh repo delete Anuj2402/gh-cli-test --yes   
✓ Deleted repository Anuj2402/gh-cli-test
anujrai@anujrai-mn4561 90DaysOfDevOps %
```


