# Task 4: Pull Requests

### Step 1: Create a New Branch

```bash 
git switch -c feature-practice
```

verify: 
```bash 
git branch
```

### Step 2: Make a Change
Append a line to your README:

```bash 
echo "## GitHub CLI Pull Request Practice" >> README.md
```
Check:
```bash 
git status
```

### Step 3: Commit the Change
```bash 
git add README.md
git commit -m "Add GitHub CLI pull request practice"
```
### Step 4: Push the Branch

```bash 
git push -u origin feature-practice
```
Expected:
```bash 
Branch 'feature-practice' set up to track remote branch 'feature-practice'.
```

### Step 5: Create the Pull Request

RUN: 
```bash 
gh pr create \
  --base main \
  --head feature-practice \
  --title "Add GitHub CLI PR Practice" \
  --body "This pull request was created using GitHub CLI."
  ```
Expected output:
```bash 
https://github.com/Anuj2402/90DaysOfDevOps/pull/1
```

Step 6: List Open Pull Requests

```bash 
gh pr list
```
Example:
```
Showing 1 of 1 open pull requests

#1 Add GitHub CLI PR Practice
```
### Step 7: View Pull Request Details

View PR #1:
```bash 
gh pr view 1
```
Example output:
```
Title: Add GitHub CLI PR Practice

State: OPEN

Author: Anuj2402

Reviewers:
None

Checks:
No checks reported
```
Open it in the browser:
```bash 
gh pr view 1 --web 
```

### Step 8: Merge the Pull Request
- Merge using the default merge method:

```bash 
gh pr merge 1
```
- GitHub CLI will ask which merge strategy to use.
- Or choose one explicitly.

Merge Commit
```bash 
gh pr merge 1 --merge 
```
Squash Merge
```bash 
gh pr merge 1 --squash 
```
Rebase Merge
```bash 
gh pr merge 1 --rebase 
```
- After merging, delete the branch:
```bash 
gh pr merge 1 --merge --delete-branch
```
Step 9: Verify
```bash 
git switch main
git pull origin main
```
- You should see your changes merged into `main`.

